[2] Cambodia
Date: Thu 28 Jun 2007
Source: Reuters India [edited]
<http://in.today.reuters.com/news/newsArticle.aspx?type=worldNews&storyID=2007-06-28T141813Z_01_NOOTR_RTRMDNC_0_India-282159-1.xml&archived=False>

Impoverished Cambodia is appealing for
international help to fight a major outbreak of
dengue fever, which has killed more children
early in this year's [2007] wet season than in all of the last.
"Dengue is hitting almost all provinces
nationwide. We cannot contain the virus with our
limited resources," Ngan Chanta, head of the
country's anti-dengue programme, said on Thursday
[28 Jun 2007]. "We need foreign help" to counter
an outbreak that has killed 138 of the 12 700
children the mosquito-borne virus has infected this year, he said.
The virus, which generally strikes during the
June-September wet season and in Cambodia appears
to hit mostly children, killed 116 of the 12 300
who caught it last year. Cambodia, still
recovering from decades of civil war and the
"Killing Fields" of the Khmer Rouge, needed 500
000 [USA dollars] swiftly to buy larvicides for
use on mosquito breeding grounds, Ngan Chanta said.
Lam Eng Hour said the 4 Swiss-funded hospitals of
which he is deputy director were being swamped by
dengue sufferers the facilities treat free. "We
just cannot manage if more and more patients come," he said.
The hospitals had appealed for 7 million [USA
dollars] from donors, he said, to fight a disease
that has reached epidemic proportions in wealthy
Singapore as well as striking hard in neighbouring Thailand and in Malaysia.
Lam Eng Hour said many children died of dengue
because the hospitals were short of blood for
transfusions, and he praised foreign tourists who
had responded to appeals by donating blood "They
are being more than just tourists, they are
saving our childrens' lives," he said.
Cambodia's public health system remains
rudimentary, with much of its funding coming from
foreign aid. According to the World Bank, annual
government spending on health is about 3 [USA dollars] per person.
--
Communicated by:
ProMED Rapporteur Brent Barrett
[A map of Cambodia can be accessed at:
