[11] Brazil (Sao Paulo)
Date: Wed 04 Jul 2007
Source: Folha de S�Paulo [in Portuguese trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www2.correioweb.com.br/cbonline/indice.htm>

In the 1st semester of 2007, the state [Sao
Paulo] had 52 566 [dengue] cases, a number
greater than the 51 566 registered in the entire
year of 2006. The number of deaths from DHF (14)
is now the same as in 2006. At least 90 of the
645 Sao Paulo municipalities are faced with epidemics.
The number of registered [dengue] cases now will
[likely] exceed the historical record of 2001,
when 51 668 persons contracted the disease.
The Secretary of Health of the state has
attributed this record [number of dengue cases]
to 3 factors: high temperatures coupled with
rains during the 1st months of the year; an
epidemic [of dengue] in the [state of] Mato
Grosso do Sul, which adjoins Sao Paulo; and
greater circulation of [dengue] virus type 3,
which causes greater dengue symptoms, and consequently, more reported cases.
According to the Superintendent of Endemic
Control, Afonso Viviani Junior, the [downward]
trend in recent weeks is due to 2 climatic
factors (dry and cold season). "This has reduced
the vector mosquito population significantly."
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[ProMED would be interested in vector control
measures that have been implemented in Sao Paulo.
A map of Brazil can be accessed at:
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/brazil.jpg>- Mod.TY.]
