[12] Brazil (national)
Date: Tues 03 Jul 2007
Source: Maracaju News [in Portuguese trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.maracaju.news.com.br/ultimasnoticias/view.htm?id=78420>

The efficiency of the country's battle with
dengue worsens. In the 1st 4 months of this year
(2007), the number of cases of this disease
increased 20 percent in relation to the same
period in 2006. There have been 246 833 [in 2007]
of which 288 developed DHF and 38 died -- a
number between 10 and 15 per cent greater than in
the same period of of last year (2006). Concerned
about this increase, a group of consultants from
the Pan American Health Organization came to
Brazil in July [2007] to analyze with local
consultants the plan to combat dengue.
According to Fabiano Pimenta (acting Secretary of
Surveillance, Ministry of Health), the increase
in cases has been due to 2 factors: an increase
in the intensity and duration of rains, and an
explosion of cases in Mato Grosso do Sul [state]
-- 68 000 cases just this year (2007). "In the
state there have been a large number of
[mosquito] breeding sites and the population was
not resistant [immune? - Mod.TY] to dengue virus 3," he observed.
He also noted, however, that in other localities,
where the population is also susceptible to
dengue [virus] 3, the epidemic was
contained. This was the case in [the state of]
Minas Gerais. "This is an example of how, with
good field work and the collaboration of the
population, it is possible to avoid an explosion
in the number of cases." he affirmed.
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[There does not exist a rapid solution for dengue
control. One can see thousands of consultants,
but the problem is not knowing what to do, rather
to [go ahead and do it, without stopping, over the long term. - Mod.JLS.]
[An economic assessment of the cost of dealing
with a dengue epidemic versus the cost of a
sustained dengue control program (vector control)
would be of considerable interest. The challenge
is financing control when there have been no, or few, cases in past years.
The WHO (World Health Organization) description
of dengue fever and the more deadly dengue
hemorrhagic fever [DHF] can be found in
ProMED-mail's "Dengue/DHF update 20070514.1541"
ProMED-mail thanks the contributors to this
update and encourages others to contribute reports also. - Mod.TY.]
